{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JajiHDopekTfn4QRaAfLNC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have everything I need. Let me design the lifecycle component. This is an atomic component, so I need to:\n\n1. Design the component concretely\n2. Write acceptance criteria\n3. Write a README.md to the output directory\n4. Emit the `<response>` XML block\n\nThe output directory is: `/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/platform-monolith/output/internal/iam/internal/iam/lifecycle`\n\nThe lifecycle component needs to implement:\n\n\n- User creation, retrieval, and deletion endpoints\n- Authentication with login and logout flows\n- In-memory storage for users and tokens with password hashing via bcrypt and UUID generation via crypto/rand\n- Thread-safe access using sync.RWMutex\n- Single `lifecycle.go` file containing User and TokenStore structs plus a Handler() function that returns an http.ServeMux with all routes registered\n\nDefining the data structures...\n\nI'm finishing the route registration with the login and logout endpoints, then wrapping everything in the handler function. I'll use Go 1.22+ routing syntax since that's the modern standard. For the implementation, I need bcrypt for password hashing, random token generation using crypto/rand, and standard library utilities for JSON and HTTP handling. The main file will be `lifecycle.go` containing all the stores, handler setup, and route definitions.\n\nNow I'm defining the ID and token generation ‚Äî both use random bytes converted to hex strings for simplicity. Looking at the error cases: missing fields return 400, missing users return 404, successful deletes return 200, and auth failures return 401. The logout endpoint needs to validate the token before clearing it.\n\nDefining helper functions... 10. POST /auth/login with unknown username returns 401.\n11. POST /auth/logout with valid Bearer token returns 200; subsequent logout with same token returns 401.\n12. POST /auth/logout without Authorization header returns 401.\n13. All handler operations are safe for concurrent access.\n\nNow I need to verify the test command path ‚Äî it looks like there's a duplicate `internal/iam` in the directory structure that I should clarify before running the tests.\n\nSince this component has 5 endpoints with full request/response schemas, I should create an `api.md` file alongside the README to document the API contract. Let me write both of those now. Continuing with the API documentation for the remaining endpoints and their request/response schemas, covering user retrieval, authentication, token validation, and logout operations with their respective status codes and error handling. I need to figure out where to run the test command from. The output package is nested pretty deep in the directory structure, but `go test` needs to be run from somewhere that has a `go.mod` file. The IMPLEMENTOR will handle setting that up, so I should make the test command relative to the module root rather than hardcoding an absolute path. Let me look at how the metrics component handled this to stay consistent.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1591,"cache_read_input_tokens":21960,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1591},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90951103-4484-400d-836d-3fb9bb5e08a6","uuid":"204446d9-cb04-4385-b3b6-0e89f21147ff"}
