ferently.\n\nFor the `/users/{id}` endpoint, manual path parsing with `strings.TrimPrefix` and `strings.Split` is the simplest approach given the package's small scope, avoiding an extra dependency.\n\nSetting up the handler routing...\n\nI need to decide on password hashing‚Äîbcrypt would require adding a dependency, but SHA256 is already available in the standard library, so I'll go with that to keep things minimal.\n\nFor the implementation, I'm planning two files: `lifecycle.go` for the core logic with the handler struct, stores, and all five endpoints, and `lifecycle_test.go` for comprehensive tests. The design uses a `Handler` function that returns a configured `*http.ServeMux`, with separate `UserStore` and `TokenStore` backed by maps and protected by `sync.RWMutex`. I'll generate IDs and tokens using the UUID package that's already available, extract path parameters by splitting the URL string, and handle HTTP methods directly inside each handler.\n\nNow I'll document the API and wrap up the response.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":929,"cache_read_input_tokens":28782,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":929},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"90951103-4484-400d-836d-3fb9bb5e08a6","uuid":"7cbb0398-ad79-4129-95e2-104945b66d5f"}
